This ramal is supposed to be quite a good birding road, but my low car struggled with the rough, rutted road. I turned back at a point that looked like I would either get stuck or rip something from the undercarriage of the vehicle. A pity, because the habitat along the first few kilometres of the road isn't good, mostly scrubby cattle pastures. Weather was sunny and hot, with scattered clouds. On the way back I stopped for a little while at a small bamboo patch at KM 2.

Today we first visited ''lagoon de capybara'' in hopes for large mammals (none) but we did see 2 Tapir and a Maned Wolf on our predawn drive to park [not on this checklist]. Then an hour in Formosa river forest and an early picnic lunch at hdqs., a rest, and then a long drive to NW quandrant of park, where we visited an isolated marsh (used as a wallow by White-lipped Peccaries; photos) and returned through the park, covering lots of good grassland habitat by van. URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS98025207	2019-02-01 19:00:43	16252	species	Vermilion Flycatcher	Pyrocephalus rubinus			1				Brazil	BR	Goiás	BR-GO							Parque Nacional das Emas	L567986	H	-18.2609794	-52.8883982	2010-07-28	07:00:00	obsr227035	S6859505	Traveling	P22	EBIRD	510	40.000		6	1	G192023	0	1	0		with guide Marcelo Padua and local ranger Renato, on trip with Rita, Dan Singer, Chris Tenney. Today we first visited ''lagoon de capybara'' in hopes for large mammals (none) but we did see 2 Tapir and a Maned Wolf on our predawn drive to park [not on this checklist]. Then an hour in Formosa river forest and an early picnic lunch at hdqs., a rest, and then a long drive to NW quandrant of park, where we visited an isolated marsh (used as a wallow by White-lipped Peccaries; photos) and returned through the park, covering lots of good grassland habitat by van. We then left park and went to a farm reserve to the south, met up with Braulio Carlos & clients, and walked out to see Giant Anteater [see separate checklist for that]

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS899869117	2020-04-24 22:13:10	16252	species	Vermilion Flycatcher	Pyrocephalus rubinus			1				Brazil	BR	Minas Gerais	BR-MG							Delfim Moreira--Barra	L3244393	H	-22.3774210	-45.2598270	2020-04-21	06:01:00	obsr536027	S67596285	Traveling	P22	EBIRD	139	3.570		1	1		1	1	0		Após a corujada durante a madrugada, o foco passou a ser as aves diurnas, que intensificavam sua atividade vocal e de forrageio, a medida que o dia clareava.--Muito frio no início da manhã e durante a madrugada o termômetro do nosso quintal marcava 8 °C, mas a sensação térmica por volta das 6:15 da manhã parecia ser ainda mais baixa, muito provavelmente pela proximidade com o rio Lourenço Velho. O Céu encontrava-se completamente limpo e sem vento.--A passarinhada matinal ocorreu ao longo da estradinha que corta a mata da Invernada, atravessando o seu interior, bordas, áreas semi-abertas próximas e as margens do rio Lourenço Velho. Depois de fazer esse pequeno trecho, me desloquei diretamente para o bairro rural da Barra e a atividade de observação de aves ocorreu nos fundos do campo de futebol, principalmente, no pequeno percurso que segue margeando o rio Lourenço Velho até o seu encontro com o Ribeirão dos criminosos. Após cobrir esse pequeno trecho, segui diretamente para o nossa casa, onde dediquei alguns minutos registrando as aves do nosso quintal, especialmente, nas proximidades dos comedouros e do bebedouro.--Um grupo de macacos-sauás (Callicebus nigrifrons) em atividade vocal, na mata da Invernada.--Uma capivara (Hydrochoerus hydrochaeris), se lançou nas águas do rio Lourenço Velho assustada com minha movimentação.----<a href="https://www.flickr.com/photos/187432716@N05/49804264252/in/dateposted-public/" title="Corujada e passarinhada, Barra, Delfim Moreira MG."><img src="https://live.staticflickr.com/65535/49804264252_9a9d136bf0_k.jpg" alt="Corujada e passarinhada, Barra, Delfim Moreira MG." /></a>----<a href="https://www.flickr.com/photos/187432716@N05/49804263927/in/dateposted-public/" title="Corujada e passarinhada, Barra, Delfim Moreira MG."><img src="https://live.staticflickr.com/65535/49804263927_8292ff51f7_k.jpg" alt="Corujada e passarinhada, Barra, Delfim Moreira MG." /></a>----<a href="https://www.flickr.com/photos/187432716@N05/49803993866/in/dateposted-public/" title="Corujada e passarinhada, Barra, Delfim Moreira MG."><img src="https://live.staticflickr.com/65535/49803993866_3ba8d11a6f_k.jpg" alt="Corujada e passarinhada, Barra, Delfim Moreira MG." /></a>----<a href="https://www.flickr.com/photos/187432716@N05/49803963781/in/dateposted-public/" title="Corujada e passarinhada, Barra, Delfim Moreira MG."><img src="https://live.staticflickr.com/65535/49803963781_f28a66a026_k.jpg" alt="Corujada e passarinhada, Barra, Delfim Moreira MG." /></a>	Macho:

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS569509145	2018-06-16 21:10:21	16252	species	Vermilion Flycatcher	Pyrocephalus rubinus			X				Brazil	BR	Mato Grosso	BR-MT							Pantanal--Fazenda Santa Tereza (SouthWild Pantanal)	L1464769	H	-16.7581146	-56.8772335	2008-09-14		obsr179592	S42103156	Historical	P62	EBIRD					0		0	1	0		Morning birding on the forest trails before departing for Pousada Araras.----From the tour report: "We returned to the gallery forest this morning, and continued adding new birds at a frantic pace. Localized regional endemics like Large-billed Antwren and Mato Grosso Antbird were complemented by more widespread species such as Stripe-necked Tody-Tyrant and Rusty-backed Spinetail. And everyone finally had a satisfying look at the migratory Rufous Casiornis. The most exciting moment came in the form of two large woodpeckers of the genus Celeus, Pale-crested and Cream-colored Woodpeckers, in the same tree. After lunch we headed north on the Trans-pantaneira to our next destination: Pousada Araras. On the way, Patrick spotted our first group of Greater Rheas and as we skidded to a halt and piled out of the van to appreciate these strange ostrich-like birds, we realized there was also a Maguari Stork farther out in the same field (photo below), and a couple of Scarlet-headed Blackbirds closer in. Not a bad stop! Another roadside stop produced our first two Whistling Herons of the tour, and before we knew it we had arrived at Araras, where naturally we were greeted by a raucous pair of Hyacinth Macaws sitting in one of the big shade trees right next to the lodge! After settling in, we took a walk out to the canopy tower for the end of the afternoon. Striped Cuckoo and Bat Falcon were nice finds, and from the tower we had a commanding view of the marsh, full of egrets, herons, and exquisite Roseate Spoonbills. A flyby of three White Woodpeckers completed the day."

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS569503301	2018-06-16 21:10:21	16252	species	Vermilion Flycatcher	Pyrocephalus rubinus			X				Brazil	BR	Mato Grosso	BR-MT							Pantanal--Fazenda Santa Tereza (SouthWild Pantanal)	L1464769	H	-16.7581146	-56.8772335	2008-09-13	06:00:00	obsr179592	S42102009	Historical	P62	EBIRD	810				1		0	1	0		Morning birding along the entrance track to the fazenda and the nearest portion of the Transpantaneira. Afternoon river excursion. Cooler and overcast today. Saw Dwarf Caiman, Giant Otter, Southern Tamandua, Black Howler, and Brown Capuchin.----From tour report: "A merciful cold front blew through during the night and we awoke to much cooler temperatures. This morning we mostly birded the open areas along the entrance track to the lodge, finding lots of new birds like Greater and Common Thornbirds, White-rumped Monjita, and the uncommon Long-tailed Ground-Dove. Seeing Chotoy Spinetail left no doubt that it is one of the most elegant of the ovenbirds, but I think some of the group would still take the elegant Black-collared Hawk over all the spinetails I could find! We got our antbird-fix from the many Barred and Great Antshrikes along the road, and another standout was the White-naped Xenopsaris, a monotypic flycatcher-like bird now thought to be most closely related to the becards and tityras. 16 Guira Cuckoos huddling together side-by-side made for an amusing picture (photo above); apparently they were not enjoying the relief of cooler temperatures as much as we were. Of course it would be hard to forget the ubiquitous waterbirds as well, and we had incredible studies of the handsome Rufescent Tiger-Heron and the prehistoric-looking Plumbeous Ibis (photos above) in roadside pools. After lunch we went riverbirding again, picking up the diminutive American Pygmy Kingfisher and enjoying for the second night in a row the distinctive Band-tailed Nighthawks bobbing and gliding over the river."		
URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS569491810	2018-06-16 21:10:21	16252	species	Vermilion Flycatcher	Pyrocephalus rubinus			X				Brazil	BR	Mato Grosso	BR-MT							Pantanal--Fazenda Santa Tereza (SouthWild Pantanal)	L1464769	H	-16.7581146	-56.8772335	2008-09-12	06:00:00	obsr179592	S42101689	Historical	P62	EBIRD	750				1		0	1	0		Morning walk on forest trails, afternoon river excursion. Hot! Saw Capybara, Brown Capuchin, and Spectacled Caiman.----From tour report: "We awoke to our new surroundings in the Pantanal and began birding the gallery forest along the Pixaím River after breakfast. Red-billed Scythebill drew oohs and aahs from the crowd right away. The more subtle Buff-bellied Hermit, Plain Tyrannulet, and Southern Scrub-Flycatcher were good sightings as well, but just could not compete with the preposterous bill of the scythebill! A male Red-crested Finch did his best to compete, showing off his fiery red crest in the soft morning light. Farther into the forest, a young Helmeted Manakin found our group a captive audience and proceeded to preen all of his feathers and stretch extravagantly as we watched, enthralled, from close range. The forest also produced Gray-headed Tanager, Moustached Wren, the endearing Masked Gnatcatcher, and Blue-fronted and Scaly-headed Parrots  foraging in a mango tree. By late morning the heat was intense and we retired to the lodge, where we found curious Gray-crested Cacholotes,  Yellow-billed Cardinals (photo above), and Orange-backed Troupials in the trees just around the house. Did I mention the enormous Jabiru nest not far from the lodge? It wasn’t until late afternoon that we ventured out again, this time on the river, heading dowstream. We visited the nest of a Great Potoo (photo below) and found Green-backed Becard and Hooded Tanager nearby. On the river, we saw dozens of Gray-necked Wood-Rails along the banks (aren't rails supposed to be shy?), as well as Little Cuckoo, Agami Heron, and Black-capped Donacobius. A giant Ringed Kingfisher perched with a huge peacock bass on his bill was quite a sight. A night drive produced Spot-tailed and Little Nightjars (incredible views of the latter perched on a fencepost), Crab-eating Fox, and Crab-eating Racoon."

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS569429057	2018-01-20 15:31:29	16252	species	Vermilion Flycatcher	Pyrocephalus rubinus			X				Brazil	BR	Mato Grosso	BR-MT							Rio Cristalino--general area and historical lists	L875406	H	-9.5972613	-55.9311079	2008-09-07		obsr179592	S42096009	Historical	P62	EBIRD					0		0	1	0		List of species from the tour checklist that are not included on the other more precisely located eBird checklists from today (Tower 1, Rochas Trail, Rio Cristalino downstream from the lodge, and the Teles Pires river islands). Saw Capybara, Brown Capuchin, Red Brocket Deer, Brazilian Tapir, and Amazonian Tree Boa today.----From tour report: "For our first morning in the Amazon we headed up Cristalino’s famous canopy observation tower, where we immediately found ourselves in the middle of a roaring mixed-species flock that included Lineated Woodcreeper, Yellow-backed Tanager, and Red-stained and Ringed Woodpeckers. Between good views of common species like White-throated Toucan, Paradise Jacamar, Spangled Cotinga, and Bare-necked Fruitcrow, we managed to see several of the local specialties, such as Curl-crested Araçari, Kawall’s and White-bellied Parrots, White-browed Hawk, and the ornate Gould’s Toucanet (photo below). Spectacular Blue-and-yellow and Scarlet Macaws provided breathtaking moments as they flew past at close range below eye level and a Brown-banded Puffbird perched unconcernedly close to the tower. (Photo below.) Descending to ground level around mid-morning we found the birding a bit more challenging inside the forest though some were able to see Bare-eyed Antbird and Cryptic Forest-Falcon right near the base of the tower. Before lunch there was time to go for a quick walk out toward the saleiro (natural salt lick) where we found a group of Crimson-bellied Parakeets (photo below) and a Black-bellied Cuckoo in the surrounding trees. A sub-canopy flock included White-winged Shrike-Tanager and Tooth-billed Wren. After lunch we headed downstream on the Cristalino, seeing some good mammals (Red Brocket Deer and Brazilian Tapir) as well as a Razor-billed Curassow coming to the bank of the river to escape the heat. We ended the afternoon birding the river islands on the Teles Pires, picking up the target Amazonian Tyrannulet  as well as a somewhat out-of-range Black-collared Swallow with a large group of migratory swallows made up mostly of Purple Martins and at least one Barn Swallow. It was especially entertaining to watch a group of Spotted Tody-Flycatchers snuggling together and bedding down on their roost just at dusk. Returning to the lodge after dark we happened upon a stunning Agami Heron while spotlighting caiman. What a day!"

After lunch we headed back to Cuiabá, on to the airport and so ended another amazing Pantanal-Amazon tour."

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS269055816	2018-08-07 14:23:37	16252	species	Vermilion Flycatcher	Pyrocephalus rubinus			X				Brazil	BR	Mato Grosso	BR-MT							Vila Bela da Santíssima Trindade -- general area	L3053997	H	-15.0079331	-59.9457321	2009-06-15	05:45:00	obsr412230	S19570752	Incidental	P20	EBIRD_CAN				2	1		0	1	0		with Jessica Davis. This morning Jessica joined the birding, and we were on the road by 05:45 heading east from Vila Bela on the road to Pontes e Lacerda. We checked out a couple of side roads before stopping for a while on the entrance road to the Fazenda Toca do Coelho. This road is located a little past KM 60, on the south side of the road, signed with a faded white sign made from an old table saw blade. Excellent cerrado along the short stretch before the fazenda. We also spent some time birding pastures and some cut-over forest along the entrance road to Fazenda Planicie (KM 45.5 of the BR-174). On the return to Vila Bela we stopped at the unmarked road across from the Toca do Coelho, which had a nice flooded field and some good cerrado farther along – I plan to check this out again at an earlier hour. Back to town for lunch at the Restaurante Paço das Onças across from the Bela Vila Hotel – not amazing, and expensive moreover!----We went back to the Hotel Cascata for a short nap, then I headed out again at 15:05. Crossed the river this time, turned south (right) at the gas station and followed the dirt road out of town and south toward Casalvasco. The winds and threatening skies from earlier in the day turned to heavy, heavy rain and I didn’t see much. Drove some 30 km south before turning back (GPS point marked MarshY). There was still time and daylight left over when I arrived back to town, so I drove up to the Parque Estadual Serra do Ricardo Franco to check things out for tomorrow. Looks like a nice place, we’ll probably have lunch there tomorrow as I plan to return to the cerrado first thing to continue the search for Black-and-tawny Seedeater. Back to the hotel by 17:50.

Marcelo Camacho, Jorge Macêdo, Ronilson, Francisco Diniz (Makunaima Expedições -Unnamed Road, Roraima, BR - Sítio morada do sol e Bosque dos Papagaios ) e JPavani  que ficou fotografou em uma ilha formada no Rio Branco, maior de rio de Roraima. Alguns bichos que sempre vemos estão fora da lista, não conseguimos observar. URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS437825875	2018-08-02 15:58:14	16252	species	Vermilion Flycatcher	Pyrocephalus rubinus			3				Brazil	BR	Rio Grande do Sul	BR-RS							Banhado do 25 / FEPAGRO -- Rio Grande	L5005689	H	-32.0036361	-52.2954798	2016-10-22	08:45:00	obsr742454	S32158696	Traveling	P22	EBIRD	345	9.600		2	1	G1976347	0	1	0		Na companhia de Maiara Vissoto. As primeiras observações foram feitas desde a entrada até a sede da Fepagro Sul - caminhamos pela estrada principal e amostramos as capoeiras de Baccharis e maricá, as manchas de pinus e eucalipto (todas tomadas por aspargo-samambaia no sub-bosque) e alguns campos úmidos. Da sede da Fepagro caminhamos em direção a um banhado gigantesco de palha-cortadeira (Scirpus) - dentro algumas corticeiras-do-banhado (Erythrina) e gravatás (Eryngium). Seguimos costeando o banhado, passando por mais algumas manchas de pinus e eucalipto, capoeiras de Baccharis até chegar em um campo encharcado à beira do banhado - campo de c. 80 cm de altura, muitas Eriocaulaceae, alguns salsos (Salix) e eucalipto na borda. Na segunda parte seguimos pelo trilho de trem (c. 1 km), que passava dentro do grande banhado de palha até chegarmos próximo a algumas casas (última parada). Na volta fizemos o mesmo caminho. Ensolarado, pouco vento, muito quente.
